## Risk matrix

| # | Risk | Probability | Impact | Mitigation |
|---|------|-------------|--------|------------|
| 1 | Low recruitment (N < 132 in 12 months) | Medium | High | Multi-site recruitment (TSU, University of Copenhagen); monthly monitoring; extend enrollment period by 6 months if needed |
| 2 | LLM hallucination causing patient harm | Low | Critical | Medical oversight by Co-I (MD); real-time LLM output filtering; mandatory disclaimer; adverse event reporting |
| 3 | Data privacy breach (GDPR non-compliance) | Low | Critical | Pseudonymisation; encrypted storage; annual GDPR audit; data processing agreement with all partners |
| 4 | PAM-13 license withdrawal by Insignia Health | Low | High | Backup outcome measure (Patient Activation Measure short form); early license negotiation |
| 5 | Reference integrity failure (e.g., incorrect PMID) | Medium | Medium | Pre-submission reference audit by two independent reviewers; use DOI where available; automated PMID validation |
| 6 | Dropout rate >20% | Medium | Medium | Retention strategies (reminders, incentives); per-protocol sensitivity analysis; oversample by 20% |
| 7 | σ estimate off by >20% from pilot | Medium | Medium | Pilot phase (N=20 per group); recalculate sample size; adjust enrollment target if needed

| Risk | Probability (1–5) | Impact (1–5) | Risk Score | Mitigation |
|------|-------------------|--------------|------------|------------|
| Privacy breach (PII/PHI) | 2 | 5 | 10 | Encryption at rest/transit, access logs, IRB-approved data management plan |
| LLM hallucination (clinical advice) | 3 | 4 | 12 | Guardrails, human-in-the-loop review, disclaimer in UI |
| Recruitment shortfall | 3 | 4 | 12 | Multi-site backup plan, extended enrollment window, social media campaign |
| Dropout >20% | 3 | 3 | 9 | Retention incentives, reminder system, per-protocol sensitivity analysis |
| API outage (OpenAI/Azure) | 2 | 3 | 6 | Fallback to rule-based chatbot, local caching of responses |
| Technical failure (platform crash) | 2 | 4 | 8 | Redundant servers, automated monitoring, rollback procedure |
| Selection bias (digital literacy) | 3 | 3 | 9 | Stratified randomisation by digital literacy score, sensitivity analysis |

| Risk | Probability | Impact | Mitigation |
|------|-------------|--------|------------|
| Privacy breach (patient data) | Low | High | Data encryption at rest/transit; access logs; GDPR-compliant data processing agreement |
| LLM hallucination leading to clinical harm | Medium | High | 4-zone HCI escalation: if AI confidence < 0.7 OR clinician confidence < 0.5 → escalate to human; 100% of high-risk outputs reviewed by clinician within 24h |
| Recruitment failure (low enrolment) | Medium | High | Multi-site recruitment (3 sites); community outreach via patient organisations; contingency plan for extended enrolment period |
| High dropout rate (>20%) | Medium | Medium | Retention incentives (monthly feedback reports); reminder system; per-protocol sensitivity analysis |
| API outage (LLM service disruption) | Low | Medium | Local fallback on Ollama (open-source LLM); automatic switchover within 5 minutes; manual protocol as last resort |
| Technical failure of AI router | Low | High | Redundant router instance; automatic failover; 24/7 monitoring with alert threshold < 2 min downtime |
| Selection bias due to co-design | Medium | Medium | Stratified randomisation by baseline activation level (low/medium/high); sensitivity analysis excluding co-design participants |


