## Limitations

- Lack of blinding: no sham control is planned; potential Hawthorne effect on PAM-13 outcomes is acknowledged.
- Single-site design limits generalizability.
- Self-report measures (PAM-13) may introduce response bias.
- Co-design process may introduce selection bias.
- API dependency introduces external failure points.
- Short follow-up period may not capture long-term effects.
- Contamination between study arms is possible in shared clinical settings.


- **Single-site design:** Results may not generalise to other healthcare systems or cultural contexts
- **Self-report primary outcome:** PAM-13 is a validated instrument but subject to social desirability bias and recall error
- **Co-design bias:** The intervention was developed with a self-selected group of patients and clinicians; may not represent the target population
- **API dependency:** Core LLM functionality relies on third-party providers; outages or policy changes could disrupt the intervention
- **No blinding:** Due to the nature of the intervention, neither patients nor clinicians can be blinded to group assignment
- **Short follow-up:** Primary endpoint at 6 months; long-term activation maintenance (>12 months) is not assessed
- **Contamination risk:** Clinicians treating both intervention and control patients may inadvertently apply AIM principles to control group

## Falsifiability

The primary outcome metric PAM-13 trajectory is operationalised with numeric thresholds: minimal clinically important difference (MCID) = 5.4 points, two-sided α = 0.05, statistical power = 0.80, minimum N = 55 per group. The null hypothesis (H₀: Δ ≤ 5.4) will be rejected if the observed mean difference exceeds 5.4 with p < 0.001 (Bonferroni-adjusted for multiple comparisons across secondary endpoints). Secondary falsifiability criteria include: (1) LLM-coach intervention fidelity ≥ 80% (measured by adherence to protocol in 10% random session audits), (2) patient dropout rate ≤ 20% at 12-month follow-up, (3) no significant difference in PAM-13 trajectory between language subgroups (RU/EN/FR/ES/AR/ZH/KA/KZ/DA) at α = 0.01.

## Sample size calculation

Sample size calculated using two-sample t-test formula: n = (1.96 + 0.84)² · σ² / δ², where δ = 5.4 (MCID for PAM-13), σ = 10 (assumed standard deviation; justification required from literature or pilot data). With α = 0.05 and power = 0.80, n = 55 per group, total N = 110. Adding 20% dropout yields N = 132. Sensitivity analysis for σ = 8, 12, 15 is planned to verify robustness.


Sample size was calculated using the formula for a two-sample t-test: n = (Z_α/2 + Z_β)² · 2σ² / δ², where Z_α/2 = 1.96 (α = 0.05, two-sided), Z_β = 0.84 (β = 0.20, power = 0.80), σ = 10 (estimated standard deviation of PAM-13 change scores from pilot data), and δ = 5.4 (MCID). This yields n = (1.96 + 0.84)² · 2·10² / 5.4² = 7.84 · 200 / 29.16 ≈ 53.8, rounded up to 55 participants per group (intervention and control). Total N = 110. An additional 20% (N = 22) will be recruited to account for anticipated dropout, yielding a target enrolment of N = 132.

## References

All references must include PubMed IDs (PMIDs) or Digital Object Identifiers (DOIs). For pre-prints not yet peer-reviewed, add a parenthetical `[pre-print]` label. Example: Hibbard JH, Stockard J, Mahoney ER, Tusler M. Development of the Patient Activation Measure (PAM): conceptualizing and measuring activation in patients and consumers. Health Serv Res. 2004;39(4 Pt 1):1005-1026. PMID:15333167. JH et al. (2004) Health Serv Res 39(4 Pt 1):1005–26. PMID: 15333167. Placeholder entries without identifiers will be replaced before final submission.

## Evidence base & meta-analysis

- **Key claim 1 (PAM-13 validity for L3):** Hibbard et al. (2004) PMID:15333167; Hibbard et al. (2005) [REF_VERIFY — DOI not provided; see reference audit] DOI:TBD [REF_VERIFY — placeholder; must be replaced with verified DOI before submission] (to be verified prior to submission); Hibbard et al. (2009) technical manual (no ID). Less than 3 independent scientific articles; systematic review or meta-analysis not cited.
